the parietal lobe","Precentral gyrus of the frontal lobe"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprecentral gyrus of the frontal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E contains the primary motor cortex (M1), which is responsible for controlling voluntary movement. This area contains a topographical map of the body, with different regions controlling specific muscle groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epostcentral gyrus of the parietal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E contains the primary somatosensory cortex, which processes touch, pressure, pain and proprioception\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior temporal gyrus\u003C/strong\u003E contains the primary auditory cortex and is involved in processing sound\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcarine sulcus of the occipital lobe\u003C/strong\u003E contains the primary visual cortex, which processes visual information\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eangular gyrus of the parietal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is an association area involved in complex language processing and spatial cognition\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary motor cortex receives input from other motor areas and projects to the corticospinal tract to control voluntary movement of the contralateral side of the body.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primary motor cortex is located in the precentral gyrus of the frontal lobe and controls voluntary movement.","The primary somatosensory cortex is located in the postcentral gyrus of the parietal lobe and processes sensory information.","The primary visual cortex is located in the occipital lobe around the calcarine sulcus."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human